<br>
However, I think the PoA rotation has mostly been in name only.  In practice, it's really more of a sign-up system.  When was the last time anyone who wanted to go there had a problem finding an empty couple of days at some point over the course of two weeks?  You may not get the exact days you want, but you certainly don't have to wait until you're near the front of the rotation either.<br>
<br>
Because of that, I don't think the rotation system is hurting anyone's chances of going there whenever they want.  At the same time, I don't know how often the rotation system is helping either.  IMO, it really doesn't make much difference one way or another.  <br>
<br>
The only thing tipping the scales for me toward the rotation is that it's a fair way to regulate the sign-ups on the off chance more than one guild wants to sign up for the same days, rather than giving the guild whose representative can post immediately when the next week's sign-ups are posted an advantage over the guild whose rep is stuck at work then.  This is really what the planes rotations have always been about, so it makes sense to me to keep it that way for the planes that can only readily support one raid at a time. <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
